{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0171ceVztRJFVdB8CS7JzuAC","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 20 → 21 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→One failure, one root cause, one fix. The 8-word filter's separator exception regex is missing `/`, causing a correctly merged continuation title to be rejected.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Failure: 8-Word Filter Blocks `/`-Separated Variant Titles\n    10→\n    11→### Root cause\n    12→\n    13→The guard at `title-extractor.ts:282`:\n    14→\n    15→```typescript\n    16→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n    17→```\n    18→\n    19→rejects `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` (10 words) because ` / ` is not matched by the character class `[+:&]`. The continuation pre-merge step correctly merged lines 54–55 into this single candidate, but `passesHardFilters` discards it. Because the merge consumed line 55, the standalone 5-word prefix `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` never enters the candidate pool either. The algorithm falls back to the wrong (truncated OCR) heading from the previous recipe on the page.\n    20→\n    21→### Fix\n    22→\n    23→Add `/` to the separator exception character class:\n    24→\n    25→**Before (line 282):**\n    26→```typescript\n    27→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→**After:**\n    31→```typescript\n    32→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&/] /.test(text)) return false;\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→This is consistent with the existing treatment of `/` elsewhere in the pipeline:\n    36→- The continuation pre-merge already recognizes `/` as a continuation character (`/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)` at line 407).\n    37→- The continuation-join protection logic already handles `/` (`/^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder)` at line 773).\n    38→- The multi-slash breadcrumb filter (line 272) already permits single-`/` titles through.\n    39→\n    40→Adding `/` to the 8-word exception makes the hard filter consistent with these existing rules.\n    41→\n    42→### Risk assessment\n    43→\n    44→**Low.** The `/` separator in cookbook titles is structurally identical to ` + `, ` : `, and ` & ` — it separates a base recipe name from a variation/subtitle. No body-text sentence uses ` / ` as a word separator, so this change cannot admit false positives. The existing 2-slash breadcrumb filter (line 272) still blocks navigation lines like `/ Jesien / Zupy`.\n    45→\n    46→### Expected impact\n    47→\n    48→- The SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS regression is fixed: the merged 10-word title passes `passesHardFilters`, qualifies as a structural heading, and wins scoring as it did in iteration 19.\n    49→- All other test cases remain unaffected (no other candidate is blocked by the 8-word filter with a single `/`).\n    50→- Real-file pass rate returns to 100% (11/11).\n    51→\n    52→---\n    53→\n    54→## No other changes needed\n    55→\n    56→No other patterns are failing. The pipeline's core architecture (continuation pre-merge → caps coalescence → candidate building → embedding scoring → structural heading selection → dedup) is working correctly for all 11 real files and all generated files. This iteration requires only the one-character regex fix described above.\n    57→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_011WCmCKBDjWkfXpzJV9GTes","session_id":"06e30cc2-e666-4ba2-b79a-bd76ce637f9b","uuid":"6172e353-d133-43b3-8611-4f92fbec7975"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017ReAr6UfyjQthJSrayfjeM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 20 — Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→1 failure out of 11 real-file test cases (90.9% pass rate). The failure is a **regression**:\n     6→`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` passed in iteration 19 and now\n     7→fails in iteration 20. The remaining 10 real files still pass.\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Pattern 1: 8-Word Filter Blocks `/`-Separated Variant Titles\n    12→\n    13→**Affected file:** `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D).real.txt` (real file)\n    14→\n    15→**Affects:** Real files only (the 8-word filter is a new `passesHardFilters` guard added in\n    16→iteration 20; the generated test files that hit the 8-word range all use ` + ` or ` : `\n    17→separators, which are already whitelisted).\n    18→\n    19→---\n    20→\n    21→### What the file contains\n    22→\n    23→The OCR page contains two variations of saffron buns from the same cookbook spread. The first\n    24→~53 lines are the body of Variation 1 (whose heading appears near the middle: `FRON WHEAT BUNS\n    25→(VARIATION 1)` — a truncated OCR fragment of \"SAFFRON\"). The target recipe starts at lines 54–55:\n    26→\n    27→```\n    28→Line 54: SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\n    29→Line 55: / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\n    30→```\n    31→\n    32→The test harness filename uses `:` as a filesystem-safe substitute for `/`, so the expected\n    33→title (after `normalize_separators` converts `:` → `/`) is:\n    34→`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`.\n    35→\n    36→---\n    37→\n    38→### Why iteration 19 passed\n    39→\n    40→In iteration 19, `passesHardFilters` had no word-count ceiling. The continuation pre-merge step\n    41→(which merges a line into its predecessor when it starts with `/`, `&`, `+`, `:`, or `(`)\n    42→correctly merged lines 54–55 into a single candidate:\n    43→\n    44→```\n    45→SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→This candidate passed all hard filters, qualified as a structural heading (`isStructuralHeading`),\n    49→and scored well on embedding similarity. The algorithm returned it as the title.\n    50→\n    51→---\n    52→\n    53→### What iteration 20 changed\n    54→\n    55→Iteration 20 added this guard to `passesHardFilters` (line 282):\n    56→\n    57→```typescript\n    58→// Lines with ≥8 words are almost certainly body text, not titles.\n    59→// Exception: multi-title compounds with \" + \", \" : \", or \" & \" separators are allowed.\n    60→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n    61→```\n    62→\n    63→The merged title `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` has 10 words\n    64→(SAFFRON, WHEAT, BUNS, WITH, QUARK, /, COTTAGE, CHEESE, (VARIATION, D)). It fails the guard\n    65→because `/` is **not** in the separator exception set (`+`, `:`, `&`).\n    66→\n    67→---\n    68→\n    69→### Why the algorithm fails\n    70→\n    71→1. The continuation pre-merge produces `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` as a single merged line.\n    72→2. `passesHardFilters` rejects it: 10 words ≥ 8, and the text contains ` / ` not ` + `, ` : `, or ` & `.\n    73→3. Because the pre-merge consumed line 55, `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\"` alone never appears in `mergedLines` — there is no standalone 5-word candidate for this title either.\n    74→4. With the correct title absent from the candidate pool, the next-best structural heading is `\"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\"` — a truncated OCR fragment from the previous variation on the same page.\n    75→5. The truncation-detection code (which penalises \"FRON\" when \"SAFFRON\" is present as a longer candidate) cannot fire, because the full \"SAFFRON…\" candidate was eliminated before scoring.\n    76→6. The algorithm returns a wrong answer derived from the previous recipe's corrupted heading.\n    77→\n    78→---\n    79→\n    80→### Root cause summary\n    81→\n    82→The 8-word filter was added to fix body-text leakage (long Polish cooking-instruction sentences\n    83→escaping into candidates after the `commonShort2` expansion). The fix is correct in principle,\n    84→but its separator-exception whitelist is incomplete. Cookbook titles often use ` / ` to separate\n    85→a base recipe from a named variation (e.g. \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE\n    86→(VARIATION D)\"). The separator regex `/ [+:&] /` does not include `/`, so these legitimate\n    87→long titles are incorrectly discarded.\n    88→\n    89→The fix is minimal: add `/` to the exception regex so that ` / ` is treated the same way as\n    90→` + `, ` : `, and ` & `:\n    91→\n    92→```typescript\n    93→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&/] /.test(text)) return false;\n    94→```\n    95→\n    96→---\n    97→\n    98→## No Other Patterns\n    99→\n   100→Only one real file fails. There are no generated-file failures in this iteration. The single\n   101→failure is fully explained by the incomplete separator whitelist in the 8-word guard.\n   102→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_011WCmCKBDjWkfXpzJV9GTes","session_id":"06e30cc2-e666-4ba2-b79a-bd76ce637f9b","uuid":"c743f61e-a776-4df0-9bff-5dc048273012"}
